\details{
\strong{What changes vs. \code{grf::causal_forest()}?} Only the nuisance
predictions used to centre \code{Y} and \code{W}. The CATE estimator, honesty
splits, and identification assumptions are inherited from \pkg{grf}.

\strong{Why TabPFN?} TabPFN is a transformer pre-trained on synthetic
tabular generative processes and frequently outperforms gradient
boosting on small-to-medium tabular regression and binary
classification tasks. Better nuisance fits reduce bias in the Robinson
(1988) residualisation step that underlies \code{grf::causal_forest()}.

\strong{Cross-fitting.} TabPFN nuisance predictions are produced via K-fold
cross-fitting: for each fold, TabPFN is trained on the other \code{K - 1}
folds and predicts on the held-out fold. This avoids using a unit's
own outcome to predict its own residual. If \code{c.forest$clusters} is
non-trivial, folds are built so that all units in a cluster end up in
the same fold (preserving \pkg{grf}'s cluster-aware inference).

\strong{Treatment type.} \code{W} is treated as binary if it is \verb{\{0, 1\}}-valued
(numeric or integer with both levels present), a logical, or a 2-level
factor; in that case TabPFN's classifier is fit and propensity scores
are clipped to \verb{[eps, 1 - eps]} to preserve overlap. Otherwise \code{W} is
treated as continuous and TabPFN's regressor is fit. If \code{W} is numeric
with exactly 2 unique values that are not \verb{\{0, 1\}} (e.g. \verb{\{1, 2\}} or
\verb{\{-1, 1\}}), \code{tabcf()} emits a warning and falls back to the regressor;
encode such treatments as \code{0/1} to use the classifier.

\strong{Tuning.} The \code{tuning} argument controls how \code{grf::causal_forest()}
tunable hyperparameters (\code{min.node.size}, \code{mtry}, \code{sample.fraction},
\code{honesty.fraction}, \code{honesty.prune.leaves}, \code{alpha},
\code{imbalance.penalty}) are handled in the refit:
\itemize{
\item \code{"orig"} (default): inherit verbatim from
\code{c.forest$tunable.params}. This preserves whatever \pkg{grf} chose
(or the user supplied) for the original forest. No re-tuning.
\item \code{"cf.default"}: omit those keys entirely so
\code{grf::causal_forest()} falls back on its hardcoded defaults. Use
this when the original forest's tuning was idiosyncratic and you
want a clean baseline. No re-tuning.
\item \code{"cf.autotune"}: omit the inherited keys and set
\code{tune.parameters = "all"} so \code{grf::causal_forest()} re-tunes from
scratch under the new TabPFN nuisances. The most expensive option
but the only one that lets the tuner respond to the new nuisance
fit. Pass \code{tune.num.trees}, \code{tune.num.reps}, \code{tune.num.draws} via
\code{...} if you need non-default tuner controls.
}
In all three modes, anything the caller passes via \code{...} overrides
the value chosen by \code{tuning}.

\strong{TabPFN seed passthrough.} Reproducibility for TabPFN is governed by
\code{random_state} inside the \code{control} argument of
\code{tabpfn::tab_pfn()}. If \code{tabpfn_args} does not already contain a
\code{control} element, \code{tabcf()} builds one per fold via
\code{tabpfn::control_tab_pfn(random_state = seed + k)} so each fold gets a
deterministic but distinct TabPFN seed derived from the user-provided
\code{seed}. If the user supplies \code{tabpfn_args$control}, that control
object is passed through verbatim for every fold (so the user is
responsible for any seeding).

\strong{Dependencies and TabPFN backend.} The \code{tabpfn} R package
(tidymodels-style wrapper around the Python TabPFN backend, v0.1.0+)
is gated as a Suggests dependency. \code{tabcf()} calls
\code{rlang::check_installed("tabpfn")} at the top and raises an
informative error if missing. The Python backend additionally
requires a one-time license acceptance: register at
\url{https://ux.priorlabs.ai}, accept the license, copy your API key, and
set \code{TABPFN_TOKEN} in the environment before calling \code{tabcf()}.
Without it, the underlying Python call raises \code{TabPFNLicenseError}.
The easiest way to set the token from inside R is to call
\code{\link[=setup_tabpfn_token]{setup_tabpfn_token()}}, which checks for the variable, walks you
through registering at \url{https://ux.priorlabs.ai/account}, and
optionally appends \code{TABPFN_TOKEN=...} to your \verb{~/.Renviron} so
future sessions pick it up automatically. \code{tabcf()} itself calls
\code{\link[=setup_tabpfn_token]{setup_tabpfn_token()}} when the variable is missing in an
interactive session.
}
\examples{
\dontrun{
library(grf)
set.seed(1995)
n <- 200; p <- 5
X <- matrix(rnorm(n * p), n, p)
colnames(X) <- paste0("X", seq_len(p))
W <- rbinom(n, 1, 0.5)
Y <- X[, 1] * W + rnorm(n)
cf  <- causal_forest(X, Y, W, num.trees = 200)

# default: inherit grf's tuned params from cf
cf2 <- tabcf(cf, K = 5)

# use grf's hardcoded defaults
cf3 <- tabcf(cf, K = 5, tuning = "cf.default")

# re-tune from scratch under TabPFN nuisances
cf4 <- tabcf(cf, K = 5, tuning = "cf.autotune")
}
}
